          "title": "Samuel's verdict — the two 'nows' that divide history",
          "body": "Samuel's response (13:13-14) is one of the most compressed theological verdicts in the historical books. Two sentences, two contrasting 'nows.' The first 'now' (v. 13) opens a conditional perfect — 'for now the LORD would have established your kingdom over Israel forever.' The covenantal possibility was real: an eternal dynasty contingent on obedience, the same covenant framework later granted to David (2 Samuel 7:16). The second 'now' (v. 14) closes that possibility permanently — 'but now your kingdom shall not endure.' The same word, used twice in consecutive verses, marks the hinge between possibility and foreclosure. John Calvin noted that divine patience with human failure does not mean divine indifference to it; the moment of judgment, when it comes, is precise and irrevocable. The verdict does not revoke Saul's kingship immediately — he will reign for decades — but it revokes the dynasty's future. His sons will not follow him on the throne. That forfeiture is irreversible."
