          "title": "A man after His own heart — the shadow of David",
          "body": "The chapter's most theologically generative phrase appears in Samuel's verdict: 'the LORD has sought for Himself a man after His own heart' (13:14). The reader in the narrative sequence does not yet know who this is — David is not named until 16:13. But the phrase 'levav' (heart) sets the standard by which the coming king will be evaluated. In contrast to Saul, who acted to manage circumstances, the man after God's heart will be one whose inner orientation — will, affection, and allegiance — aligns with the LORD's own purposes. The phrase does not mean a man who is sinless (David's record in chapters 11-12 of 2 Samuel forecloses that reading) but a man whose heart, when confronted with failure, turns toward God rather than toward self-justification. Tim Keller's observation is pointed: the difference between Saul and David is not the presence or absence of sin but the response when confronted with it. Saul explains; David confesses (Psalm 51)."
