          "title": "The arms-shortage — material consequence of spiritual failure",
          "body": "The chapter's closing section (13:19-23) documents the military consequence of both Philistine dominance and Israelite faithlessness in concrete economic terms. The Philistines had deliberately eliminated ironworking from Israel — no blacksmith could be found in all the land (13:19). Israelite farmers had to pay Philistine prices to sharpen farming tools they could not repurpose into weapons. The result: on the day of battle, the entire Israelite army had no swords and no spears except for Saul and Jonathan (13:22). The material poverty is not incidental — it is the narrator's way of showing that spiritual disarmament and material disarmament coincide. A people without faith in their king, led by a king without the LORD's favor, standing on the battlefield with no weapons in their hands: this is the picture with which chapter 13 ends. Chapter 14 will show that the arms-shortage does not stop Jonathan — but that is the next chapter's story, and it belongs to a man who does not share his father's fear."
